&quot;there's a lion and a giraffe. they're like hanging out. there friends.&quot;this rather unconventionally structured joke was my first introduction to a rather great bar. &nbsp;probably should have led with the termite joke. &nbsp;a little bit of a hidden gem, the glendale tap is a great bar -- filled to the brim with tchotchkes, taps and pool tables, homey without feeling artificial. &nbsp;the genuinely friendly (occasionally quirky) staff, almost driven to dirty dishes will let you try what seems like everything (and it is appreciated). &nbsp;no word yet on whether you could actually try all 52 taps. &nbsp;plus! beer here is pretty cheap, going for $6 up to 9 and down a couple of bucks for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> (which runs for two <span class="highlighted">hours</span> after 5. &nbsp;not <span class="highlighted">happy</span> with just dirtying glasses, they have peanuts you can eat and encourage to throw on the floor with wild abandon. &nbsp;&quot;you here for awhile?&quot; &quot;why do you ask?&quot; &quot;you picked the twenty minute long song...&quot;a little worried about the digital jukebox in the corner, they've made sure to limit it to songs you should be listening to -- jazzy numbers and the like. &nbsp;there were also some christmas songs mixed in for some mood music for some writing regulars. &nbsp;&quot;my brother plays the flugelhorn.&quot; did i mention there was a good crowd?
you know those tv shows/movies where there's a bunch of twenty somethings and they all convene at a cool low key spot to shoot the shit, play pool, and drink beer once a week? this is that spot.i almost didn't want to write a review on this place because it's such a great gem, i don't want other people to know about it! &nbsp;come with your crew, order a beer you've never tried before, grab some peanuts and throw the shells on the floor, play some pool, and pick some sweet tunes from the jukebox. &nbsp;it's got a worn-in, small town feel. &nbsp;nothing pretentious about this place. &nbsp;it reminds me of a bar my parents would have hit up when they were my age. &nbsp; &nbsp;i'm not really a beer expert, so the bartender made a lot of educated suggestions for me to try. &nbsp;i had a pear cider, an ipa, and some locally brewed beer, all for less than 15 bucks during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>! &nbsp;i definitely recommend the ciders if you're not into strong beers. &nbsp;they're sweet, flavorful, with just a hint of alcohol. &nbsp;normally, i feel weird going out with my sober friends, but not to glendale tap. &nbsp;even if you're not drinking, you can still have fun here.
terrible service. wont be back. came in with a friend and were definitely made to feel unwanted by the bartender. not sure what it was about since he was being nice to the other people in the place. best guess is that the only visible difference between my friend and i and the rest of the patrons is that we were the only non-white people in the place. besides being rude, he did amateurish, foolish things. first off he didn't know when their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is. secondly if you ask him to taste a beer, he acts annoyed. then if he gives you a taste of something and you don't like it, he gets really annoyed. &nbsp;then he proceeds to pour you the beer you finally order in the glass he gave you a taste in. so if you tasted a hoppy ipa and left a gulp at the bottom but then end up ordering a bock, he just pours the bock on top of the ipa. a place that boasts about its 52 taps should have more respect for its beers and its customers.this place is a dump don't waste your time.
glendale tap rules, other beer bars drools. &nbsp;let me tell you a story: i went here one early evening with a pal to yap about work and whatever, and we bellied up to the bar. &nbsp;we were informed that it was <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, which meant $2 off every pint. &nbsp;i requested a basket of peanuts, because nothing is more awesome than eating dry roasted peanuts while you drink cold beer, listen to rock music, and throw the gd shells right on the gd floor. &nbsp;then, after being informed of the crazy special barrel of craftsman whathaveyou that they were featuring off-menu, and after perusing the list of the 50+ craft beers on tap, i picked the best one: &nbsp;a nitrogen-poured pint of miller high life. &nbsp;&quot;nitrogen pour&quot; is how, say, guinness is served. &nbsp;where most beers are forced out of the keg via carbon dioxide, this was not. &nbsp;it's rare to see it with non-stouts/porters, and rarer still to see it used as an alternative way to enjoy a beer you're familiar with as a co2. &nbsp;and i had certainly never seen that before with the &quot;king of the uncle beers,&quot; miller high life (my personal favorite of the cheapos, so i knew i was already in the right place if they had this as the only &quot;major brew&quot; on tap).the feeling? &nbsp;well, as i described it to my pal tim, as we sat at the bar shelling peanuts: &quot;if the back of this bar rolled up, and we found ourselves magically transported to the upper deck at dodger stadium, this would be the best day of my life.&quot;and not just because it meant we had discovered that magic was real. &nbsp;but because this nitrogen poured high life tasted like a beer slushy, without the slush. &nbsp;it was cold, and smooth, and the most perfect thing i could imagine to go with baseball, which i don't really care that much about. &nbsp;but it rules with beer and being outside in the sun. &nbsp;the cost to me for this mini-vacation? $3.00 usd. &nbsp;i followed it up with the craftsman, which was an ipa that was fermented w/o hops (they were added later to a red ale, i believe). &nbsp;i drank it, and said, &quot;this tastes like ipa tea.&quot; to which the bartendress added, &quot;it basically is. &nbsp;the fresh hops are in there in tea bags.&quot; and it wasn't carbonated at all, just tapped, and poured out of the barrel. &nbsp;man. &nbsp;it was tays-tea. &nbsp;i got drunk on that, and went across the street to eat tacos. &nbsp;the end?
(drank 04/11/13 th @ 10pm): i proudly tapped this watering hole!after a wonderful yelp elite event at the nearby icis apartment homes, several of us weren't ready for the evening to end so we hauled our arses to the glendale tap located on the border with los feliz for some after-event libations...as if we didn't get enough already!i had just dropped off my +1 from the elite yelp event and was already feeling pretty good with the amount of alcohol content in my body, but when fellow yelper schel h. and aren a. said they were going to hit it up, that sounded like a party to me. laura s. also attended along with others.we found ourselves at the very far end of the bar past the pool tables and next to the restrooms. you ordered at the bar to get your choice of libation, of which they apparently had 52 taps <a href="http://www.yelp.com/user_local_photos?userid=8jvt2inwc8giq6sh2ug9vw">yelp.com/user_local_phot…</a> of lovely liquid elixirs from your standard brews to a multitude of craft and microbrews. they also had some in bottles, but when you have that many taps why grab a bottle with you can get it fresher!? throughout the night i ended-up with two microbrews which totally escaped me now ($6.00 ea.), but they were ice cold, refreshing, and hit the spot. and the company i was with made them even that much better! oh, and i can't forget to mention the complimentary bowls of peanuts which helped to soak up any alcohol. we just cracked them open, dumped the shells on the floor, and once the bowl was empty we went to the bar and asked for me. that's how it's done! the service was good from the time they checked my id at the entrance to the two bartenders (the woman had a cuteness about her). you ordered at the bar, they served you, and that was it. there was one person who walked around and collected any empty glasses. very easy-peasy.parking was no bueno since they didn't have their own and it was all on the street (metered until 8pm), either along the main strip of san fernando rd. or the surrounding streets (where i parked). it's a bit industrial and kind of sketchy at nighttime, so be warned.overall, the glendale tap was a nice place to escape, grab a drink or two, and hang with a bit more of a biker-ish crowd if not a grungier clientele on the outskirts of the emerald city. i found good value based on the prices, service, and experience noted above (total bill was around $15.00; tip included), but it would've been so much better if they had late-night <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. the atmosphere, d&eacute;cor, and ambience was pretty divey, dark, rustic, and a handful of tables and chairs all along the wall. the walls were covered with an assortment of old license plates, posters, and other oddball marketing or otherwise material. it kind of reminded me of the crap that was pulled out of the bowels of one of the sharks in the movie &quot;jaws&quot;. there were two free pool tables that took up the majority of the space in the center of this two-car garage-sized building. they also had a food case that displayed empanadas and other simple treats. and i saw two tvs, a jukebox, and there was a songlist machine where we were at for your auditory entertainment. the tunes were pumping with 70's and 80's rock. the attire was totally casual so i would normally be in a t-shirt, boardshorts, and flip-flops. and they accepted my credit card of choice...amex!
i wanted to hate this place before i stepped foot inside. there was a dude with a handlebar mustache and a crew of other nondescript twenty-something hipsters wearing acid-washed jean shorts and oversized cropped band tees. i had already decided i'd stay for thirty minutes, wish my buddy a <span class="highlighted">happy</span> birthday and take off... but i fell a little in love instead. peanut shells on the floor, free pool, a killer digital jukebox, tons of beer selections, even non alcoholic bitburger beer, root beer, and ginger beer for people such as myself who spend sober <span class="highlighted">hours</span> in bars watching everyone get wasted. they also happen to have an owner from chicago, and the bar itself is made from a portion of a bowling lane from miami bowl on the southside, where my husband used to bowl as a kid! pretty sweet, and it's one of the few bars in my neighborhood too. i have to admit, even the hipsters i met were pretty damn cool. i've been back since, and i'm sure i'll be back many, many more times.
