wow...from the exterior i would have never expected the griffin to look the way it does from the outside. &nbsp;this place is fab! &nbsp;i finally found a home away from home. &nbsp;it's a little castle-esque meets haunted mansion. &nbsp;the only reason i say haunted mansion is that the way the lighting hits the paintings on the wall, i think they pictures are moving! &nbsp;(and no, i wasn't high).i was surprised to find there were no tvs here because every &quot;loungey&quot; type place in la has 'em but i think that's a really good thing. &nbsp;it forces you to do something that you don't do all that often, talk. &nbsp;and something i do even less often, listen. &nbsp;the music on the jukebox is very diverse and you'll really find comfort in that. &nbsp;me being a 5 senses kind of person.the drinks are great, the sofas/seats comfy, fire pits are lovely. &nbsp;this griffin i feel is a bit better than the one in vegas because it's roomier. &nbsp;however, go to the one in vegas if you get a chance. &nbsp;it's in the newer &quot;revitalized&quot; part of downtown and it's a nice chance to get away from the tourists, ringing slot machines and expensive drinks. &nbsp;i can't remember the last time i paid for a drink in vegas (other than getting them free at the tables) that was less than $10...the guinness there was $5. &nbsp;i haven't been to this one on the weekend yet but i am finding if i need a place to &quot;hoan&quot; my skills (ie. talk and listen), i'll come here for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> during the week...which works to save a few buckaroos. &nbsp;go, you won't regret it!
this place is a good neighborhood bar. it's big and there's usually always a place to sit, and they have an outdoor enclosed smoking patio. the fireplaces are always burning which is a nice touch. the food is mediocre but i've been there enough times to know which items to order (no to the fried pickles, but the fries are okay). while the majority of their staff i find to be friendly and competent, there is a bartender named john who's rude and slow. the last time i visited the griffin during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, john was outside having a cigarette. he had seen us enter and although he was the only bartender on duty, my friend and i sat at the bar for 10 mins while john finished smoking outside. when he finally took our order i asked him about one of the specials pairing a beer with a food item. i'd never heard of that beer before so i asked if there was an alternative to which john replied with a straight face &quot;i could just not give you the beer.&quot; rude! my friends and i have all made complaints about this bartender and hopefully he improves his performance/attitude or is replaced. on busy nights, the lines to get a drink are ridiculously long. they need more/better bartenders! otherwise, the bar is an okay local hangout. decent music always playing and good drinks.
be warned, they have a very strict policy of no hats with any sports team logo. i don't know if this extends to shirts and jackets, but hats with a sports team logo are definitely not allowed. some of the staff is cool about this policy and will reprimand you nicely , some of the staff (the manager jason g, specifically) gets very upset and will yell at you if you violate the rule. so just avoid to hassle of getting treated like you're some kind of idiot and leave your hat in the car. i didn't like getting yelled at by the manager jason g as i was getting up to leave and accidentally put my hat on too early for his liking. all this after hiding it under the bar all evening. anyway... &nbsp;the buffalo wings + mango/habanero sauce is awesome, but the wings are tiny. the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> price is 5 wings for $5 which is a bit pricey. the crostini was really tasty, but again the portion was on the small size. tots.. my god.. what can you say that hasn't been said already?..seriously? can you mess up tots? but they were forking good!. when i arrived (7.30p thu) street parking was packed and i ended up with a couple minute walk, but by the time we left the street seemed to have cleared out (9p). the decor is pretty cool and there were plenty of places to find a seat. there is a good balance of bar, table and lounge type seating that are spread across an open room with fireplaces. overall it was ok, but i see a lot of room for improvement. i'd go back, i guess, &nbsp;unless i'm wearing a hat that i don't want to take off.. in which case.. i can do better...since posting this this morning, i have received a letter reprimanding my review from the manager jason g. he obviously thinks i am acting &quot;extreme&quot; in my assessment of his actions and my experience at the griffin. i'm sure he'd love to hear from you if have any questions. <a href="http://www.yelp.com/user_details?userid=c8n7i1sdemxzpw_pk6tsna">yelp.com/user_details?us…</a> he obviously doesn't review, but rather looks for reviews concerning his aggressive nature in dealing with customers.i dropped the rating from 2 to 1 after reading in his letter that he, &quot;wasn't too stressed about it&quot; and that i &quot;actually seemed apologetic for forgetting about the hat rule, quickly removing it.&quot; the only issue was.. i was stressed about your abrasive and inconsiderate behavior and you didn't care.. until i wrote this...cheers!
i've been to the griffin in las vegas in dt vegas on fremont street but heard there was one in silver lake. decided to check this place out on saturday night. my birthday is next month and wanted to find a spot not so much where there is dancing but a place that's low key where we can mingle with each other and have a great time. as soon as we pulled up i knew we had a winner. valet parking (not expensive). as soon as you walk it was the same as the vegas location but smaller. the dim lighting and the fireplaces made some good memories come to mind from my vegas adventures. the place was busy with patrons but not so busy that you couldn't walk around. i like that they have an outside patio area where patrons can smoke. the drinks were great and i thought reasonable but the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> specials can't be beat. they have a food menu with great selections,which we didn't try but looked good. this location has a juke box which was playing some great music that night. they do have a back room but you have to guarantee 500 people. they do have a smaller area in the corner that you can reserve for a party of 10-20 people. the waitress was great and the bartender good. you get a variety of a crowd that is not stuck up! same as the vegas location. i don't know if they have a live dj on saturday nights at this location but he vegas location does. if the silver lake location does than it's a bonus for us! i will be booking my space for next month for sure.
the first time i was at this place was a month or two after it opened last year in 2007 when my cousin's friend had his birthday there. i had my birthday <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> w/ co-workers later that year and have been in awe of the place. i haven't been back to this spot until last night, where i met up w/ a few co-worker friends and my neighbor, who told me it was their 1 year anniversary night. since it was their 1 yr anniversary, they had $1 draft beers from 8pm - closing so i texted any of my friends who i thought would be interested and would actually meet me there. now, when i went for my birthday, they weren't able to serve food yet, but last night i ordered a tomato-basil pizza and chicken strips w/ home made potato chips. i must say, i liked the freshly made personal size pizza and the chicken strips were all breast meat. they have an a rating from the l..a. county department of public health (i didn't expect anything less!) too! :)the women's restroom is pretty clean for those of you picky about that. although i never went up to the jukebox to pick music, whoever was picking it was doing a pretty good job - i didn't hate it, and actually kind of liked it. it will probably be a regular place for me to go and just chill (by myself or w/ friends). i don't have an excuse, it's not even that far from my place.kudos goes to my neighbor who told me about the anniversary special! i would not have known, nor gone yesterday had it not been for him. one of my favorite parts of this bar is the fireplace, as well as the overall decor. it's got this medieval, yet contemporary feel to it. if you smoke, the outdoor patio is pretty comfy with cushiony seats (similar to bay-window type seating) to just hang out and chill. there is no cover charge, and when i went last night, i went after work dressed in sneakers, jeans and a polo. at least i didn't have to go all the way home to change. parking is just tough to find, but nothing will stop me from going there b/c of that. i'll just go early like i did yesterday ;)
i love drinking just a little bit more than i like eating. &nbsp;i should do a drinking blog, but it would get boring really fast. &nbsp;each post would go something like this: me at bar, me ordering a pint of beer, me making new friends and then me convincing those new friends that i'm o.k. to drive myself home. having said that, i love givin' props to a good drinking hole and tonight that hole the griffin this dungeon-esk bar is the newest edition to the atwater village/los feliz/glendale area. the interior feels like a posh dungeon, complete with ceiling and walls made of stone bringing an old english comfy feeling to a dungeon atmosphere (ok enough with the dungeon). two fireplaces, comfy, cushioned booths, and outside patio area a brilliant jukebox stocked with the creme-de-la-creme of indie-rock (the cure, the smiths, echo and the bunnymen, the postal service, elo, ). if you are there and someone is playing arcadefire in it's entirety, chances are that's me sitting up at the bar sipping on a stella. the best thing about this bar? the staff, the manager andrew and the &nbsp;bartenders esther, patience, shane, steve, and shannon rock so hard you'd &nbsp;think they were paying me to say this until you experienced it for yourself. so i was all set for night of high class boozin'. &nbsp;i was with some friends and we were intrigued by the interesting mix of people: retro punk rockers, t.v. writers, and guys in suits who probably left work for a quick drink and found themselves on an accidental bender. &nbsp;they'll probably show up at the office tomorrow in the same suit smelling of booze and strippers. &nbsp;i know. i know. you're getting thirsty aren't you?long story short: the pours are potent, the staff is rad, and the jukebox is good, they have a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> that starts at 5, and are even going to be serving food very soon... is that tater-tots i smell? yeesss!!!!!
piss poor customer service, but fantabulous food.this place may excel with its fantastic food and tasty drinks, but its reputation (in my opinion) is seriously hurt by the ridiculously poor service these me-against-the-world servers and employees with piss poor attitudes.a zero out of 5 for service.we came in on a saturday afternoon (~6:30) during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and sat in the corner. for 15 minutes almost, we sat there, unless someone told us in such a tone &quot;umm, it isn't 9 yet, so you're going to have to go up to the bar and order yourself&quot;. gee, no shit, thank you for the condescension. already i was beginning to feel apprehensive about the place.so i went up to the bar and ordered two drinks and some food. they gave me the little placard to put at our table. and nothing else. so i went to sit down.about 5 minutes later this guy in skinny jeans, a beanie, and a scruffy ass bead comes with more condescension... &quot;did you order drinks? you're going to have to go and pay for them now&quot; as he rolls his eyes. yeah, no shit hipster. i didn't steal the drinks, they weren't even made for me yet.this same guy gave us stinking attitude at least two more times during our evening... i won't go into details, because thinking about it makes me see a white hot light. so anyway... he and the other 5 employees that were there went to sit down at the bar again and talk and have drinks and food, instead of helping out the only customers there. oh, right... did i forget to mention that we were the only patrons at the griffin until about 7:30 and we were still getting treated like shit?ok at this point i was fuming and was getting ready to punch hipsterboy in the kidney and make him piss blood, but then our food came out.amazing food. seriously. a 6 out of 5.blt with tater tots, an order of fries to share, and a mini burger.mind blown. the blt was a little buttery but flavorful. they made a blt taste more amazing than i've had at any other place. the fries were crisp with a hint of pepper with homemade ketchup.... and the miniburger was coated with a tent of cheese.afterwards, we had the ice cream sundae with homemade french vanilla ice cream... i've never had $12 ice cream, but somehow i knew this was worth the money.needless to say overall i was amazed by the food... and still a bit ker-fluffed (is that a word) about the piss-in-my-drink service.so this place gets a (6+0)/2. would be better, but won't be until the employees take a step back and take the sticks out of their asses. it took them 15 minutes to close our tab.my final words about this place? expect shitty service, especially if you're not dressed like a hipster. i think if my pants were tight with my twig and berries stuck like a division symbol, i would have been able to communicate with these people. more specifically... if you see an employee in skinny jeans, a deep v shirt, a beanie, with a scruffy ass beard, walk away. he thinks you are trying to oppress him and will treat you as such. find another employee... they will be slightly nicer.
love it, love it, love it. i'm biased, because i work there (security), but i hang there too. the decor is great! medieval comfort, with plenty of leather couches and 2 bars when it's busy. the fireplaces are wonderful when you're coming in out of the cold, especially while it was raining over the past month. not many bars have a heated, well ventilated smoking patio. that alone takes this spot to another level. i can sip my scotch and smoke my cigars in comfort, without being overwhelmed by other people's smoke either.the crowd here is very cool, especially the regulars and locals. i love the neighborhood, and the patrons reflect the laid back, personable professionals that have populated the area. there's some youngins from time to time, but for the most part i'd say the age range is 25-40, and generally good folks to share a drink with anytime.it gets pretty crowded on the weekends, and sometimes there's a line after 10pm, usually only when a lot of birthday parties fill up the place. the griffin is great for groups, and the word is definitely out! we hate to start a line, but usually you won't be waiting for longer than 10 minutes or so. plus you can always walk a few blocks down to the roost or bigfoot lodge for a bit, and come back when it's settled down. you will be back, trust me. it's the swankiest spot on the block!there's a lot of lovely ladies coming through here on the regular too, which is just wonderful! as if the place needed more or a draw, and then ya fill it up with hotties! thanx to all my fellow yelpers who have helped make this a great place to work.rarely will you see a scuffle, thanx to the awesome crowd who frequent this place, and when something does go down, it doesn't last long. it's just not that kinda party. since people usually show up in groups, they take care of one another anyways, so the belligerent a-holes are generally escorted out by a friend rather then necessitating security to step in. it's nice.if we do have to handle something, i bet you we'll be as respectful as possible. we consider our patrons like friends for the most part, and will treat you as such.i wish the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> food was better, and i'd love to hear a little more funk from the jukebox, but the drinks are good, and there's an impressive selection of liquor as well.gotta love it.ps - i wrote r.n. a response to her review, which is totally bullsh*t. i hope her friends will offer counter-reviews after witnessing the night's events first hand.04/24/08 update: &nbsp;we now sell parliament, marboro red, and camel light cigs at the bar! no more lamenting over the liquor store next door being closed so early. and, mainly to appease our wonderful regulars, you can buy a loosey for a quick fix, and avoid the guilt of buying a whole pack! i only smoke cigars, but i must say, i was impressed by this new addition. kudos management....and now, to wait for the check &nbsp;;p
