god knows i am a sucker for themed bars. but this place earns its stars for more than the decor, which includes a 'fire'place, mounted animals on the walls, a carved wooden bear on the bar, and large footprints outside the entrance. the bartender, whose name i didn't catch, but who had long black hair and looked a little morose (though engaging enough), pours with such a heavy hand you'd think you're really in the woods at night and the only thing to keep you warm is the fire in your belly he's supplying.<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> runs from 5p-8p, $1 off anything. my boy got smokey's moonshine, a shot of fruit infused liquor served warm-this will knock you on your ass if you drink the sweet concoction on an empty stomach. &nbsp;i had a sasquatch, wild turkey, ginger brandy, ginger ale, and bitters served on ice in a tall ass glass. seriously, the glass was taller than me and i had to bend the straw in get in there. the bartender filled said glass with 3/4 booze but i was in the bathroom at the time, enjoying the reading material on the stall door, so i came back blissfully unaware that i was about to get buzzed off of an inch of tasty drink. wowee. the moonshine was $4 (!!!!) and mine was a worthwhile $9. &nbsp;music on not djing days is nostalgically awesome.
(drank 05/10/13 f @ 6pm): the only hairiness i saw was the facial kind found on the collection of hipsters here!my buddy and i took a couple weeks off from our weekly <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> excursion (which usually happened on mondays) for various reasons, but it was back on this friday night and i needed a place that had later <span class="highlighted">happy hours</span> because of work, and the bigfoot lodge fitted the criteria. another friend was able to join so it was a party of three!we each arrived within minutes of each other and grabbed a cushiony leather booth directly in front of the bar - location, location, location! the bigfoot lodge had daily <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> from 5pm-9pm with a very limited drink menu (only five drinks), but the drinks were priced at $5.00 each so dammit i was going to work it, and we all did!:bigfoot collins ($5.00 x 2) - i started the evening on a light foot with this concoction of bombay gin, lemon juice, simple syrup and a splash of perrier. this definitely has a sweetness to it from the syrup but overall truly refreshing. <a href="http://www.yelp.com/user_local_photos?select=21y-quyvgvkxcreyzbtqjw&amp;userid=8jvt2inwc8giq6sh2ug9vw">yelp.com/user_local_phot…</a>gimlet ($5.00) - next up was this mixture of vodka, lime juice, and simple syrup. again, a light drink but this time not as sweet and a heavier pour of vodka; thank you! however, a bit too much ice for my taste. <a href="http://www.yelp.com/user_local_photos?select=g5qlplr-88bznkvkb8mcra&amp;userid=8jvt2inwc8giq6sh2ug9vw">yelp.com/user_local_phot…</a>old fashioned ($5.00) - i'm not necessarily a fan of this drink which consisted of bourbon, bitters, simple syrup and for show a flaming orange zest (but only lasted for a second!). the strength of the sweetness was back but in this case it defused the taste of the bourbon a bit which i liked. my buddy thought it tasted too much like black licorice. <a href="http://www.yelp.com/user_local_photos?select=_is3uc5y2zu3hlahis-7aw&amp;userid=8jvt2inwc8giq6sh2ug9vw">yelp.com/user_local_phot…</a>tullamore dew ($5.00) - i've never tried this irish whiskey before, and although i enjoyed it neat and sipped it lovingly, this one almost did me in, so after i polished this off we went next door to grab some indian food takeout and brought it back. <a href="http://www.yelp.com/user_local_photos?select=ot7cbmo9w98w87ukhzr2nq&amp;userid=8jvt2inwc8giq6sh2ug9vw">yelp.com/user_local_phot…</a>scrimshaw pilsner ($5.00) - i needed something to wash down my indian food and this was the last item to try on their &quot;$5 buck <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>&quot; menu. i liked this lighter beer and actually went well with my food.service - it was great since it was still relatively empty. we had a clear path to the bar to place our orders and the cute pigtailed female bartender who wore a ymca indian princess vest (i knew this because of my nieces) was quick with our drinks and even brought them to our table one time.parking - they don't have their own lot but there was plenty of metered street parking ($2.00 - $1.00/<span class="highlighted">hour</span> but free from 8pm-8am) as well as the side streets.overall, this review was a longtime coming for the bigfoot lodge as it's been a favorite of mine for some time and a great place that my friends and i hung out in. although they didn't serve food, it was way cool that they allowed outside food to be brought in. and, apparently a food truck would show up later in the evening. i found great value based on the prices, service, and experience noted above (total bill was around $30.00 before tip), but the hh prices were hard to beat and even the regular prices weren't bad either. the atmosphere, d&eacute;cor, and ambience was a rustic dark log cabin with a wilderness motif. there were leather booths and couches as well as bar stools and sitting cubes that surrounded the faux fireplace towards the back. the tables were of sectioned tree cut-offs and the bar also had a similar design. there were random stuffed animal heads, national forest signage, and other woodsy memorabilia. there were no tvs but there was background music which we managed to here the loop all the way through. the attire was totally casual so normally i would've been in a t-shirt, boardshorts, and flip-flops. and they accepted my credit card of choice...amex!
so, i've lived across the street from this place for more than 2 years, and i finally made it in about a week ago. the decor was charming(gotta love the near-life-size smokey the bear!) and the music is 80s! gotta love that too! but, the drinks were unremarkable and it is a little too loud for my taste. i like to be able to hear my friends at the neighborhood bar, its not like this is a vegas dance club. the clientele is also hit or miss. on the night i was there, there was a pretty raucous bachelor party (i was deaf for the rest of the night from their obnoxious whistling) but i guess that can happen at any bar. but, all in all, it was a cool place, but i'll probably frequent it for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and not on saturday nights anymore.
shocking as it may be, i am not really an outdoorsy kinda girl. yes i was a girl scout and i can sell cookies and pitch a tent with the best of them( though the uniform has a whole different look now, i gotta tell ya). i can appreciate nature as long as i get a hot shower and a warm campfire to snuggle by.that's why this kitchy bar is so great, you get the fee-ling of being in the outdoors in some rustic cabin without actually hiking or getting dirty.i personally love a themed bar and this one definitely has a sense of humor about itself. no i dont love stuffed heads on the wall, but... seven grand has the same thing going on, just sayin'. eh, i was &quot;probably&quot; too buzzed to let that part of the ambience bother me for long.i personally think the drinks are good, the &quot;girl scout cookie&quot; was delish ( even though austin said it &quot;looked like paint&quot;) but by far, the &quot;toasted marshmellow&quot; was my fave. i mean they toast a marshmellow in your drink people, what else could you want ?( be forewarned it has 151 in it among other things and it'll kick yo' ass).obviously the sexy bartender uniforms have already been mentioned by other reviewers but uh...lemme tell ya no scout i ever saw looked that freaking good. i had a fantastic time with my fellow yelpers, what a great way for a girl to spend her drun...uh birthday. loland yes, part ii will be held at the strip club down the street.wonder if they have <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>? ..
it was one of those days where things just happened, and an ever-increasing-in-size group found ourselves here on a sunday evening. bigfoot lodge is smack dab in hipster headquarters, yet is is as unpretentious as can be. we parked at the free meters, seated ourselves on the big, cushiony barstools, and nerded out with the super cool bartendress. it was comfortable enough that we stayed for <span class="highlighted">hours</span> (and drank for <span class="highlighted">hours</span>, which made for a terrible, horrible, no good, very bad monday).i had been to this bar's westerly cousin, bigfoot west, and was pleased to see many of the same drinks. and <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> on weekends! all drinks were $5. i started with an old fashioned, which is one of my favorites in general. it was smoky, sweet, and came with a flaming orange peel garnish. if you like being drunk and watching things burn, staring fascinated at the fire through your boozy haze, this is the bar for you. the toasted marshmallow cocktail with the flaming marshmallow garnish is another one of my favorites, as is the green, minty girl scout cookie. both are sweet, but pack a mean punch. beware, because we all sure got punched. we had a great time, drinking, chatting, inviting more friends out, getting to know the bar staff, and ordering one too many drinks. el flamin taco is walking distance, too. the bar doesn't serve food, but they are cool about patrons bringing their own in.i don't give out 5 stars liberally, but i had a great time!
i was standing at her bedside and clutching her hands, moments before my grandmother died. &nbsp;as the tears stubbornly slid down my cheeks, i tried -- through the mumbled resonance of her voice -- to listen intently on her last words.&quot;grandson,&quot; she said. &quot;make me proud. &nbsp;make sure you always study hard, and do your best to be at the top of your class. &nbsp;make sure whatever you decide to do, you do it with passion.&quot; &nbsp;her big, plump feet stood firmly erect, and peeking out of the bedsheets.&quot;i will grandma faye....i will.&quot;soon after, her eyes turned flaccid, and her grip softened. she had passed on. &nbsp;those words, immortal, have been etched in my mind ever since.it's been 20 years hence, and i have taken it upon myself to make grandma faye proud by seeking and finding the best pubs in the los angeles area. &nbsp;&quot;why, yes!&quot; i thought to myself. &nbsp;an idea to be marveled by most! &nbsp;after all, it was at one of these gin joints that my grandma met my grandfather. &nbsp;i'm sure she's looking down at me from heaven, with a smile on her face and a nod of approval.of course, when my grandfather passed on, his last words were &quot;don't be an idiot!&quot; &nbsp; so, who am i kidding? &nbsp;it was my excuse to drink beer...with a passion.this very passion, and my thoughts of grandma faye, led me to the bigfoot lodge. &nbsp;what makes this all the more ironic and interesting was my grandma faye's fascination with the legendary bigfoot. &nbsp;whether it had anything to do with her own feet was no concern of mine. &nbsp;but i knew me being here made total sense. like...it was meant to be. (but you should also know that the thought of a good brew gives me romantic notions, so take what i've said with a grain of salt.)the bigfoot lodge looks like a cabin at some ski resort. &nbsp;my grandma faye was an avid skier back in the day, as tales were told. &nbsp;kismet? &nbsp;the long, narrow bar features a fireplace near the back, if feng shui is at all a concern to you. &nbsp;it's not to me, so let's focus on the beverages.there's an array of beer on draft, consisting of hefeweizen, guinness, newcastle, pabst, and stella on tap. &nbsp;<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is 3 <span class="highlighted">hours</span> every day, between 5 and 8 p.m. &nbsp;of course, when i'm not feeling plebeian, i sometimes opt for their signature drinks. &nbsp;i personally like the &quot;sasquatch&quot; -- wild turkey, ginger brandy, ginger ale, and a &quot;dash of bitters,&quot; and the &quot;dudley do-right&quot; -- canadian club whiskey, amaretto, cranberry juice, and lime juice. &nbsp;but sometimes i don't want to spend that much, so i'll stick to the pabst if a night of heavy drinking is on order.as i got drunk off the cheap pabst, i couldn't help but think that my grandma faye would be proud. &nbsp;i had just seen beerfest and i was living the american dream -- to drink beer and make it matter. &nbsp;in my case, it was all for the g-faye.this place is a &quot;throwback&quot; bar in every sense of the word. &nbsp;if i had been of beer-drinking age in the 70s, i'm thinking this would've been the rendezvous spot for me and my friends. &nbsp;not once did i have a bad time here, and i've always managed to strike a conversation with the amiable, but consistently busy, bartenders.my first time here, an ex-girlfriend bought me a shirt as part of my birthday present. although we are no longer together, i still wear that shirt often. &nbsp;wherever i go, people comment on my shirt and notice bigfoot the bear on the back. they'll say &quot;your grandma faye was a sweetheart of a woman.&quot; &nbsp;i scratch my head and wonder what they're talking about, and why.and then it makes sense.
bigfoot spotted at the bigfoot lounge! my bad; that just my girlfriend's feet. no really, bigfoot was really spotted there. no, that's just a drunk nude robin williams. joking besides, the bigfoot lounge is a pretty unique bar to find in los angeles &amp; san francisco. sadly the one in sf, closed. &nbsp;i have been to both of them. you can say, the place is ill with cabin fever. it's look like something made out of lincoln logs. full of stuffed mounted animal that would make peta angry, the place has this old west or deep south/ european black forest decor look to the place. actual polished wood bar and tables, dark leather chairs, mason jar string lights, forestry. sadly, it's a bit too dimly. i do have to say, sporting a fireplace is a plus. honestly, it's just as rare to see, a bar like this, in such in a liberal area like los feliz. like the ultimate hide &amp; seek champion, sass-quath, this place is yeti for a party! as of this date of writing, this is the menu. first off, there is the classics like bigfoot old fashioned (buffalo trace bourbon, demerera sugar, angostura bitters with flamed lemon peel) for $11. the lodge mule (russian standard vodka, flesh lime, home-made spiced ginger beer, bitters) for $10. saza-squatch (bulleit rye, peychaud's &amp; angostura bitters, pernod rinse, with orange peel.) for $10. &nbsp;there is a number of draught beers for your harry and the henderson's type of family to pick from, ranging in price from $7 to $9. example of these drinks are allagash white, scrimshaw pilsner, murphy's stout, golden road ipa, golden road brown, unibroue la fin du monde (12oz). let's say, you're more like a can or bottle person because you're a wookie drinker. well, chewbacca, they got the drinks for you. &nbsp;pabst blue ribbon, bud light, corona, anchor steam, amstel light, shiner bock, boddington's, stella artois, xingu black lager, wyder's pear cider, chimay red, o'douls, and others for prices ranging $4 to $12. let's say you want to have a boogie night with the goofy movie staying alive bigfoot. well, there are drinks to last all night long, with roasted 'schmella (bacardi rum, 1921 crema liqueur, ferner branca, honey syrup, and a roasted up marshmallow) for $11. yes, roasted up marshmallows on fire!!! oaxacan campfire (del maguey vida mescal, espolon silver, fresh lime, chili-infused agave nectar) for $11. last is the bigfoot's hairy fire balls (fireball cinnamon whisky, fresh lemon, honey, angostura bitters, house-made spiced ginger beer) for $10. big foot has a great <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> ($5 specials until 9pm). the bartenders are dressed up like sexy, boy scouts and girl scouts. scout honor, they honestly look pretty charming in those uniforms! i just waiting for ed norton from moonrise kingdom to show up to join them. &nbsp;do ask the bartender about their sasquatch &amp; smokey beer + shot combo for $10. the places always host some type of event, from having live band music playing, dance night, trivia night, bingo night, pine car derby, stand up acts, and karaoke nights. if you sing 'oh, i'm a lumberjack, and i'm okay' on karaoke night. it will make my night. there are several large circular booths, good for groups of like 5, maybe 6, plus additional seating. comfortable floor pillow. there is an animatronic oddly place smoky the bear at the entrance for some greatly need bear hugs during smoke breaks. just don't tell, joe camel that he's taking his job. smoking are outdoor area/ patio only. still, a lot of people that come in there, have really bad odor when coming back from smoke breaks. they smell like death. the patrons depends on which day, you go are pretty mellow. i say, it's mostly a 21 to 45 age crowd. most of the time, they're friendly, but you do get a few alcoholics and asses, there to start problem. you do get a lot of hipsters, here. (after all, it's la). the restrooms are hit or miss in the clean department, depending on the days, you go there and how busy. street parking is always available and safe. still, on busy nights, it might be hard to find parking. women's restroom are supposed to have 2 clean stalls, plenty of toilet paper, paper towels, and 3 mirrors. men's restroom are supposed to be just as clean. dear readers, the bathroom are label &quot;doe&quot; (women) or &quot;buck&quot; (men) so don't you get confused. you go into the wrong room, you're road-kill. &nbsp;talking about doe &amp; bucks. credit cards are welcome. overall: it's worth checking out once. it beats going to the other bars near the area. at less, this one has a nice theme to go with it.
