one bad apple. &nbsp;brian s. definitely spoiled the bunch. &nbsp;barbrix is a little neighborhood gem. &nbsp;but sadly, i doubt i'll ever return. &nbsp;i live a few houses away. &nbsp;a dear friend from high school was in town overnight and i said 'let's walk over to barbrix. &nbsp;you'll love it.&quot; &nbsp;the lovely hostess helped us find a great little corner of the bar. &nbsp;brian s., the bartender, immediately greeted us and helped us get settled. &nbsp;then he brought over some menus and mumbled something really fast under his breath. &nbsp;i only caught the word &quot;wine&quot; and i thought i caught the words &quot;<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>.&quot; &nbsp; he was talking a bit fast and low. &nbsp;so i re-reasked to clarify which wines were on <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>.brian s. looked me square in the eye. &nbsp;put his hands on the bar in front of me. &nbsp;and shot out &quot;i just told you.&quot; &nbsp;silence. &nbsp;boom. &nbsp;no smile. &nbsp;no clarification.i laughed uncomfortably. &nbsp;my friend stared in silence. &nbsp;brian kept his stance and glare. &nbsp;clearly, he wasn't joking.so i chose to apologize. &nbsp;i'm not sure for what. &nbsp;but i said &quot;i'm so sorry, i guess i didn't really hear that part.&quot; &nbsp;brian said, &quot;yah, i just told you these wines are on <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>&quot; and half-pointed again to wine list that was covered by the food menu. &nbsp;i felt shamed and embarrassed in front of my friend. &nbsp;i just quickly ordered something i already knew on the menu to try to move past the moment. &nbsp;i couldn't enjoy the food or the wine. &nbsp;i just wanted to have our drink and move on.one bad apple. &nbsp;a forever rotten branch on an otherwise pretty tree.
