if you do go to barbrix, go during their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. &nbsp;selected beers and the wine is half off which is a steal. &nbsp;the service was very attentive and the place itself is nice. &nbsp;a great place to hang and catch up with friends or go out on a date. &nbsp;the food was good. &nbsp;not bad, but not great. &nbsp;the plates are a little expensive but that's what you expect when you go to a tapas place. &nbsp;the portions are small so you have to order a few plates to fill yourself up.what we ordered:1) deviled eggs- &nbsp;has boquerones (white anchovies) which added a nice taste.2) porcini mushroom arancini- delicious. &nbsp;fontina stuffed mushrooms packed with rice, breaded in crumbs and later, fried. &nbsp;crispy delight! 3) lamp chops- good. &nbsp;we had them medium rare. &nbsp;the portions were small for the 17 dollar price.4) spanish sausage- really good. &nbsp;served with pickled red cabbage and their sweet onion mustard. &nbsp;overall, good food and a good place to hang out. &nbsp;however, we were still hungry after so when we left, we went across the street to tomato pie to get a slice of pizza to fill us up.
first things first: the music blaring here is way too loud! it seems more appropriate at a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> type place like barbarella, but people are trying to have conversations here.the food? very good. the burrata was the winner of the night. creamy and rich, floating on your fork like a puffy cloud. the blistered shisito peppers were blackened until tender, to the point where even the stem was edible, with the salt grains adding a definitive crunch. the crispy grilled polenta and duck leg confit were both rich and nicely textured. only loser of the night was the rosemary ham, which tasted not much different than what you can get in the deli aisle at trader joe's. this was surprising given how well prepared everything else was.the wine menu is not bad, but i think they can afford to be a little more adventurous with the selection and provide bigger pours if they're going to be called a wine bar.all in all i'd give it a solid recommendation and i will be back. the list of good restaurants in this area just keeps growing!
omg, the polenta/mushroom dish was the best thing i ate during my time in la. it was small and simple - basically a disc of polenta sitting in a creamy mushroom sauce - but i could have eaten four of those things if i didn't have so much else to try. at the time i called it &quot;the most subtle use of gorgonzola i've ever experienced.&quot; awesome.a lot of the other things we tried shined as well. the charcuterie board was a steal - $17 for a giant plate of 5 delicious meats. definitely try the prosciutto! we also had a very good beet salad and a veal bratwurst that was tasty but quite didn't stand up to my wisconsin-infused standards for spicy brat-y goodness despite the tasty pesto it was sitting on.service was very attentive - plates were cleared quickly, and our server was helpful in picking our dishes. it also looks like it'd be a great place for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> - there's a big, square bar, the atmosphere is 'chic homey,' and the wine selection is excellent.
why write a positive review, when they have so many? &nbsp;because we've been going since opening week, and still absolutely love this place! &nbsp;we try and hit many of the hot new places, but we're happiest when we come back to barbrix. the atmosphere is wonderful, especially the seating at the bar - open and perfect for sharing specialty cheese/charcuterie/small-plates/wine with good friends or for date night. &nbsp;the entire wait staff is considerate and professional. &nbsp;co-owner claudio is always gracious and accommodating. &nbsp;the bartender brian is awesome. &nbsp;he's very helpful suggesting a great wine or new dish. &nbsp;favorites: deviled eggs - boquerones (marinated anchovies) makes this flavor/texturecharred octopus salad - so good! if you are at all curious, try itpork belly - delicious sweet/savory korean bbq on mini lettuce bedcrispy brussels sprouts - and the roasted cauliflower made me love vegetablesscallops - perfectly seared, flavorfulhanger steak - killer mustard/peppercorn sauce. the boyfriend loves this onetips: if you don't like a place that's a little loud, go on a quieter night or time. &nbsp;the seating atmospheres vary, so find an area that suits you. &nbsp;don't miss the open bottle wines on the chalkboard, <span class="highlighted">happy hours</span>, and st. peter's ale! the quality &amp; care at barbrix makes me proud of this local la spot.
it was someone's birthday recently. my friend and i were scrambling to find a decent restaurant that can accommodate about 15pax without having to resort to reserving shakeys, bucca di bepo, fridays or houston's. not that there is something wrong with that. yes, really.we finally decided to call barbrix because we were running out of options and the big night was just a week away.for one, it's conveniently close. i mean, &nbsp;i can throw a stone and probably break the glass door. well, maybe i'm exaggerating but it's just down the hill from the house. and if we ended up getting terribly sloshed -which we intend to do that night - we can easily walk back to my place although i'm not really looking forward to that especially we might run into some skunks and the occasional coyote.we got there and the maitre'd already knew who we are without having to tell him the name on the reservation. &nbsp;the place was packed, busy, and buzzing - figuratively and literally; tt was only a matter of time that we too were going to be.with bottles of red wine on the table and food served, we were set for the night &nbsp;that lasted until about 11pm.basically, food is good. i'm won't rave about it. i won't complain about it. &nbsp;it was more the people in the group and the amount of wine being imbided that made our visit here pleasantly surprising. a couple standouts were the pork belly and, yes, the cocktail weiners, err, i mean, the camtimpalitos. total damage for the night? $50! a deal. and no, it wasn't <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>.however, for a place that has a long list of small plates, they could have easily come up with a few creative desserts. what's good about sex if i'm not going to have an orgasm? right?a brownie?! come on...and one last thing. i totally hate a restaurant that frames any press &nbsp;clippings. it's like a living room filled with framed college diplomas. it's just tacky. 3.5 stars. and that's generous.
wow, i wasn't expecting to be as blown aways as i was by this restaurant. &nbsp;i think part of the reason is because under categories on the yelp page, it's listed as tapas/small plates. &nbsp;when i think tapas, i think olives, manchego cheese, iberico ham,etc (spanish fare). &nbsp;my particular palate doesn't rejoice at those words. &nbsp;and i've had exceptional quality ham (can't remember if it was iberico) sliced from a certain hotel in beverly hills. it's like selling excellent filet mignon....to well, someone who doesn't like filet mignon. &nbsp;as per a friend's suggestion, i decided to try this place anyway &amp; i'm glad i did! i also delightfully discovered that it wasn't exactly spanish as it was a fusion of mediterranean influences that were served on small plates of deliciousness. &nbsp;we had reservations made days before we went that were changed to a little later (hey life is hectic sometimes)...and then the day of, we both realized that due to the unpredictability of traffic, we were there early! the hostess/wife and owner were still accomodating which was much appreciated because we've all been to certain restaurants that are not (those restaurants shall be nameless because i don't like to bring forth bad karma, as evidenced by my reviews)we declined to have wine w/ our meal because we had a show (which had 2 drink minimum per person) to get to but i'm sure the wine would have taken the great food to another level. i've noticed that they have a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and cooking classes both of which i plan on returning to try. &nbsp;for a more in depth experience &amp; picture: <a href="/redir?url=http%3a%2f%2frenaissancediana.typepad.com%2f&amp;s=1e314b610067fafd407f309a897d4dfdb4a14d516b0df17ccfb0477f0fa473bd" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">renaissancediana.typepad…</a>
cannot beat $5 mimosas for brunch. came here with two girlfriends for some lovely brunch and mimosas. i made reservations the night before for 11am and didn't seem like i had to make reservations. however, 30 minutes later, it was pretty packed. everyone was taking advantage of the $5 mimosas and having a great time. the people are all so very nice and welcoming.restaurant is clean. my friends and i all got the fried chicken sandwich with the pretzel bun. it was pretty good! as you know, we also got the $5 bottomless mimosas. the only catch is that each person must order an entree over $12 to get the $5 bottomless.parking is not too bad here on a saturday morning. you can either valet park for $6 or street park. it is $1 per <span class="highlighted">hour</span> on the meters with a 2 <span class="highlighted">hour</span> max. we left here full and <span class="highlighted">happy</span>.
love this new place. great staff, menu and vibe. i'd eat outside next time because it got too stuffy, and loud, after just an <span class="highlighted">hour</span>...though the bar in back could be a <span class="highlighted">happy</span> option, too. a lovely sculpted plate of burrata with artichoke, red peppers and black olive was divine, however the halibut was disappointing: too salty and overcooked. yet what a great reminder that i would enjoy cooking more with sunchokes and chard. <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to go back and continue sampling their sweetly edited offerings.
done.barbrix has lost my loyalty. i applaud that you've become the it brunch place in the los feliz/silverlake/atwater area. i wish nothing but success for any restaurant. but the longevity lies in the way you treat your guests. and the service today was horrendous. we were a party of three without a reservation. we waited for our table with our friend because we talked so highly of barbrix. we were sat at 12:24. i looked because we were quoted an <span class="highlighted">hour</span> wait and was surprised that is was quicker. we weren't greeted by our server until a good five minutes after we had sat. that's fine, you're busy. we knew what we wanted. i made a joke about the raise in prices for bottomless mimosas: barbrix went from an insanely low $5 to $8 this weekend. i honestly never understood how they made money with $5 unlimited and thought it smart to finally raise it. $8 is still a steal. our server responded with &quot;i just work here.&quot; okay, fine. servers hear stupid jokes all day, i'm sure. we ordered two appetizers, three entrees, and bottomless for all. we started with their &quot;prosecco cocktail&quot; which the server originally said was earl grey but ended up being spicy mimosa. no big deal. i specifically told her we do not care if we are refilled with mimosas. we will gladly switch. we just wanted to try the &quot;cocktail of the week.&quot; well, we may as well ordered the &quot;drink slowly because nobody will ever come to refill it&quot; cocktail, because that's what happened. we watched as other servers carried pitchers of glorious mimosas around to their tables and joked and laughed and danced (okay, maybe not danced) with the tables around us. the table directly behind us had sung <span class="highlighted">happy</span> birthday, and had two refills of mimosas from their server as our glasses sat barren. finally, our server comes back and says &quot;oh, looks like you need more mimosas!&quot; leaves and comes back with our first refill. so now we're on our second mimosa and we've basically finished eating. we drink and chat. she comes back and clears our plates. glasses are more than half empty (a metaphor for this brunch). server returns, check in hand. &quot;do you want dessert?&quot; we say &quot;no, thanks.&quot; she drops the check. no, &quot;one more round before you go?&quot; no, &quot;anything else?&quot; just a check drop. ooooookkkkkkkk then. so we sit and chat, just hoping somebody will offer. just a basic customer service thing. &quot;hey, more mimosas from this pitcher i'm carrying!?&quot; nope. so as server of the year finally walks by i have to do the &quot;excuse me!&quot; and get her attention. i hate that. i only use it when it's an emergency. she comes over. &quot;may we have another refill please?&quot; and judging by her face, that translated into &quot;your mother hates you.&quot; because she was upset. like literally upset. as if we had been inundated with mimosas for the 40 minutes we had taken up her table (i know they're busy. we weren't there long at all). we had had two each. two. sorry, but if i'm going to a bottomless brunch, two is not cutting it. she poured that refill and you could tell on her face she was thinking &quot;choke on the pulp, bitches.&quot; so we got our third refill and finally stick cash in the bill. seriously, the second we stuck that money in the check the hostess swooped in like it was her ticket out of there. ok thanks hostess with the <span class="highlighted">happy</span> face...nah, i won't go there. server comes back with change and all the sudden she's so chipper! sorry, girl. i won't be made to feel like shit because i ask for a 3rd mimosa during unlimited mimosas brunch when we hadn't even been there an <span class="highlighted">hour</span>, not only ordered entrees but apps as well (i'm guessing most people don't order apps at brunch), and you treat us like we're a bother. we left 10%. sorry. but that's what attitude gets you. and we won't be back. ever. hyperion public and barbarella both treat you so much better for the price.
this review is not of the &quot;soapbox&quot; genre, but there were a few things about my trip to this place last night that *really* bugged me. before my friends and i left, i solemnly (read: drunkenly) vowed to the group that i would write a yelp review of barbrix. well, it's tomorrow now, and i'm not drunk anymore. so, without further ado...i met a group of people at barbrix last night to celebrate the birthday of a good friend. the service started out fine - the restaurant wasn't too busy, and we ordered a couple of bottles of wine and a number of plates. no thang. the waitress seemed to be on top of things. (attention: perception is not always reflective of reality. more on that later.)the meal was going off without a hitch, but i started to get annoyed when the bus boy (er, man) kept trying to clear plates that clearly still had food on them. bitch, when i pay good money for a burrata &quot;salad&quot; (read: small blob of cheese atop some kind of sundried tomato-tasting compote and, like, one slice of eggplant - for the record, it tasted great, no hate there), i want to finish that shit. in fact, it wouldn't matter if it was an $8 burrata cheese blob or a fucking paper container full of liquefied nacho cheese - bottom line, i'm a patron of your business, and i'll let you know when i'm finished with my plate, thanks. i don't like being hustled out of any restaurant, but it's especially inappropriate during normal business <span class="highlighted">hours</span> (the sun had yet to set), when there are (literally) 10 other people in the building, and where you're paying $16 for three veal meatballs. i finally had to say to him, &quot;if there is still food on the plates, don't take them. thanks.&quot; guh.we nosh on - the wine is flowing, the food tastes great. as the night draws to a close, we ask for the check, blah blah blah. so the waitress brings it out. the check clearly stated that the total was $320 and change. total. including tax. we gave her $80 cash and asked her to split the rest on four different cards (yes, i used to wait tables, and no, it is not hard to split credit cards, even if there are 10 of them, i promise). note that everyone in our party - all of us having worked service jobs at some point or another in our respective lifetimes - is in the habit of tipping at least 20%, and we are always <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to pay an included gratuity when it is included, but there was, for the record, no gratuity listed on the check. nada. zilch. zeroski.old girl brings the cards back with the receipts for us each to sign. i immediately notice that the totals are inflated (read: wrong) - she charged us each $67 and change, when the total for each of us should have been $60 and change. so there i go, mathy mcanal, fingers furiously tapping the numbers on my phone calculator to figure out precisely where her calculations had gone wrong and from whence she might have pulled this magical new number. all i'm going to say about that is that i still don't know what she did or what calculator she was using. (the calculator that overcharges people, apparently.)[insert semi-drunken &quot;i'm going to write them up on yelp tomorrow!&quot; comment here.] at this point, i was through dealing with the waitress. i didn't even call her over - not that she was anywhere to be seen, of course, a problem that had become increasingly bothersome as the night drew on, but i digress. i told my friends what to tip (much less than we had originally intended to, as she was clearly going to make some money off of what she had already erroneously charged to our cards) and left. it's the silver lake paradox - &quot;foodie&quot; food served with american apparel 'tude. seriously, i get better service at my local donut shop, where my average (okay, twice-yearly) purchase is less than $2.whatevs. i'm sure i'll be back, because when in silver lake, do as the silver lakeians do, but day-um, do i hate paying good (read: any) money for shitty service. unexcusable, unacceptable, unconscionable.i'd like to conclude my review by noting that we still tipped sneaky mcbitchlerson 18%. how's that for taking the high road?
