good for lounging - not for foodiesim reviewing after my second second visit, but had a similar experience the first time - i just wanted to try this place again before i made up my mind.bon vivant's a relaxing atmosphere, resplendent with beautifully ornate dishes and decor. &nbsp;conversely i've found consistently slow and . . . inadequate service (they incorrectly over charged me on both occasions) and fattening but flavorless food. it seemed like an earnest attempt was made: i could taste the fat that went into my pot pie, my mac and cheese - wonderful texture and perfectly baked - but none of the flavor. no flavor at all. my wife and i both looked at each other confused. it was like when you're sick and can't taste anything - except we weren't.the char-grilled oysters were ok - excessively coated with parmesan cheese - more cheese than oyster.the charred kale salad was an effortless behemoth of raw kale leaves with burnt edges - not what i was expecting at all. after a couple of bites, we left it untouched.a big plus: the mixed drink i had, was, amazingly delicious - as in, ignoring the food and service, i'm coming back for that. the bartender was excellent.the yogurt with granola, berries and honey was very good - a lot of honey (read: a lot of honey).the two times we went: a sunday lunch and a thursday around 11:30am, much of the clientele seemed to be the long-term lounger - and this is a good place for that. laptops, stay at home moms, typing and chatting - no one seemingly touching their food or drink.i will come back i think: for hanging with a big cup of coffee or my drink at a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> - just not for the grub.so 2 stars. one for the atmosphere, one for my drink. minuses to the food, service and overall experience.
